        <TD bgcolor='dimgray' valign='top'><font color='white' face='Verdana, Arial, Helvetica' size='2'>Now back to normal mode.  <img src=icon_smile_cool.gif border=0 align=middle></P><P>Really, AO sounds like a great and fun game to play but i'm just seeing alot of promises and what ifs.  Instant transportation, no down time, solo any dungeon, and customization of rooms really sounds good but i can point out a few problems.  Combine instant transportation, solo like a god, and little to no down time and you have some serious imbalance.  Think what EQ would be if everyone could insta port to any zone, solo well, and be full life and mana after 1 minute or less.  You'd be lucky to get any kills more or less find any good monsters (one major problem with UO).  </P><P>Customizable rooms?  Dang that sounds soooo good, I'd love to have my own little EQ room with a little poster of Najena and little pet goblin  <img src=icon_smile.gif border=0 align=middle>.  But realisticaly, what on earth is about 2000-3000 of those going to do to the game?  I'd say make lag go through the roof.  All those detailed little items in their own very detailed room.  *shudders at lag*  </P><P>Class balance, ummmm a mix of classes and skills?  So that would be the equivalent of a monk using back stab?  Or a nec using block?  A warrior that can sneak/hide  Sounds like the class distinction is a little blurred.  Wouldn't really be much point in playing a Mage or Necro if you could throw the same spells as a warrior.    If classes get too many skill of other areas then it causes them to be a one man army (again like UO) but if you make them too staganant and unflexible (like EQ) you have extreme dependencies on other classes (warriors to clerics, wizard to enchanter etc.), class envy, and "seemingly" lack of power.  Its all good and nice...until of course you get thousands of people like this.  I'd love to have a meleeing, clarity casting, backstabbing, complete healing, super necro but I certainly would hate to see the effect 2,000 would have.  Not even mentioning tanks, vehicles, machine guns, sniper rifles, laser guns, grenades, and the all too historically unbalancing rocket launcher.</P><P>Bugs...now this one is something no one can tell.  EQ didn't have any seeminly major bugs when it was done with beta (weren't we suprised).  Of course half the things we consider bugs, verant calls features (getting killed by a griff outside of the inn while you're in it).  You can't really deal with them until you smack 300,000 people in a game and have them play it for 2 years straight...while adding new zones and features, of course.</P><P>Lag, this is something we are just going to have to wait on.  It's fairly impossible to determine the amount that will occur in the finished game.  Beta four isn't going to tell you squat about how much you'll get until every zone is packed and the game is running at full steam.  EVERY game in the later testing stage isn't going to have a hint of lag.  You just don't have the amount of people or have your resources split severeal ways like in a full version.    Luckily EQ doesn't lag unless you have 100 people on your screen trying to cast spells.  Unless your computer sucks (My computer spoils me).  As for one server...AO supports 100,000 people per server...EQ supports an average of 2,600.  Something is up here.  I know for a fact that technology hasn't improved THAT much to have about a 3800% increase in total amount of players on at once. </P><P>Graphics...pretty much personal preference.  I see alot of people who just love UO graphics and some that are crazy for AC graphics.  I really don't think the SS that you provided were any good, vox.  Then again, it has been my experience you have to have it on your screen before you can really know what they are like.</P><P>"The Man",  now there's something EVERY game MUST deal with.  Think that big company has you at heart when they make the game?  *snicker*.  Origin and VI are well......not very nice.  Always thinking of the almighty dollar....how can we keep more people in game?  How can we make gameplay last longer?  How can we addict gamers?  How can we make something time consuming?  Pretty much they keep you happy for awhile.  I didn't really notice the Nerf Bat beatings until 8 months to a year after EQ came out.  That's pretty much how long it takes to get an addicted player base that will keep playing and coming back no matter what you do.  Gaming companies actualy do addiction studies to see how long it takes a certain game to become addictive to a certain type of gamer and to what degree.  You get 3 mil a month from these things and you'd be pretty darn underhanded too.  It's just a matter of how long it takes, how much pressure to make money they are under, and how much they can push your buttons before the genreal player breaks. </P><P>Bonk me over the head a couple time if I missed anything.  <img src=icon_smile.gif border=0 align=middle></P><P> </P><P></P><P></P><P>~Taleldar Dreamslayer<BR>51st DE Heretic<BR>Morell Thule</font></td>
